  "prompt": "What is the best book on the meaning of life?",
  "response": "The \"best\" book on the meaning of life can be subjective, as it often depends on personal beliefs, philosophical perspectives, and individual preferences. However, here are some widely acclaimed books that explore the theme of the meaning of life from various angles:\n\n1. **\"Man's Search for Meaning\" by Viktor E. Frankl** - This profound work recounts Frankl's experiences in Nazi concentration camps and explores how finding meaning in life is crucial for psychological well-being.\n\n2. **\"The Myth of Sisyphus\" by Albert Camus** - This philosophical essay discusses the absurdity of life and the quest for meaning, ultimately suggesting that we must create our own purpose.\n\n3. **\"Being and Time\" by Martin Heidegger** - A seminal work in existential philosophy, it delves into the nature of existence and how we understand our being in the world.\n\n4. **\"The Art of Happiness\" by the Dalai Lama and Howard Cutler** - This book combines Buddhist philosophy with psychology, offering insights into how to cultivate happiness and meaning in life.\n\n5. **\"The Purpose Driven Life\" by Rick Warren** - A Christian perspective on life's meaning, this book outlines a 40-day spiritual journey to discover one's purpose.\n\n6. **\"Tuesdays with Morrie\" by Mitch Albom** - This memoir reflects on lessons learned from a dying professor, touching on themes of love, work, and what truly matters in life.\n\n7. **\"The Second Sex\" by Simone de Beauvoir** - While not solely about the meaning of life, this book examines women's roles and existence, prompting readers to consider freedom, identity, and purpose.\n\n8. **\"A Philosophy of Life\" by William James** - This collection of essays reflects on life\u2019s meaning from philosophical and psychological viewpoints.\n\nSelecting the right book may depend on what resonates with you personally\u2014be it philosophy, spirituality, psychology, or literature.",
